pull_request.title: Implement whitebox testing of constructor arguments
pull_request.body:
<!--
Thanks for contributing to Valkey GLIDE!

Please make sure you are aware of our contributing guidelines [available
here](https://github.com/valkey-io/valkey-glide/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md)

-->

Implement a framework for retrieving the protobuf ConnectionRequest message
that the PHP ValkeyGlide and ValkeyGlideCluster constructors generate.

Add tests to validate various command inputs by examining the message
deserialized into PHP protobuf classes.

Fix various bugs:
- When using multiple addresses only the first address was used.
- Reconnection strategy was not being used.
- Client AZ was not being used.
- Connection timeout was not being used.
- Disabling periodic checks did not disable it correctly.
- Made defaults for connection timeout and reconnection strategy consistent with Rust client.

Integrate tests into CI:
- Register the test class
- Install PHP dependencies through composer in CI
- Generate PHP protobuf objects in CI
- Add dependency on symfony-polyfill to resolve issues finding ctype_* functions

### Issue link

This Pull Request is linked to issue (URL): [#2]

### Checklist

Before submitting the PR make sure the following are checked:

- [x] This Pull Request is related to one issue.
- [x] Commit message has a detailed description of what changed and why.
- [x] Tests are added or updated.
- [x] CHANGELOG.md and documentation files are updated.
- [x] Destination branch is correct - main or release
- [x] Create merge commit if merging release branch into main, squash otherwise.

Fix NULL pointer dereference in mp_obj_get_type
pull_request.body:
### Summary

If a list's comparison function calls array.clear() and gc.collect() during sort, an element slot can become MP_OBJ_NULL. Guard mp_obj_get_type() to avoid a NULL dereference and raise a proper exception instead of crashing.

Closes: #17941

### Testing

Tested on Unix port.

issue.title: Uncaught Error in Assignment of type Iterator[int] to type Iterator[str]

labels.name: bug
labels.description: mypy got something wrong

labels.name: topic-type-context
labels.description: Type context / bidirectional inference

issue.body:
<!--
If you're not sure whether what you're experiencing is a mypy bug, please see the "Question and Help" form instead.
Please consider:

- checking our common issues page: https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/common_issues.html
- searching our issue tracker: https://github.com/python/mypy/issues to see if it's already been reported
- asking on gitter chat: https://gitter.im/python/typing
-->

**Bug Report**

<!--
If you're reporting a problem with a specific library function, the typeshed tracker is better suited for this report: https://github.com/python/typeshed/issues

If the project you encountered the issue in is open source, please provide a link to the project.
-->

Mypy allows the assignment 
it: Iterator[str] = iter(d) where d is dict[int, str].

**To Reproduce**

https://mypy-play.net/?mypy=latest&python=3.12&flags=strict&gist=05c55a654acd175b763be1c73567a107

```python
from typing import Iterator


d: dict[int, str] = {1: 'A'}
it: Iterator[str] = iter(d)  # mypy does not complain, although iter(d) has type Iterator[int]!
s = next(it) + 'foo'  # TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: 'int' and 'str'
```

**Expected Behavior**

<!--
How did you expect mypy to behave? It’s fine if you’re not sure your understanding is correct.
Write down what you thought would happen. If you expected no errors, delete this section.
-->

Mypy raises an error such as
error: Argument 1 to "iter" has incompatible type "dict[int, str]"; expected "SupportsIter[Iterator[str]]"

**Actual Behavior**

<!-- What went wrong? Paste mypy's output. -->

Success: no issues found in 1 source file

**Your Environment**

<!-- Include as many relevant details about the environment you experienced the bug in -->
mypy Playground  
- Mypy version used: mypy latest 1.17.1
- Mypy command-line flags: --strict
- Python version used: 3.12

<!-- You can freely edit this text, please remove all the lines you believe are unnecessary. -->

comment.body: Yet another case where `NoMatch`/`@no_match`/`@type_error` for overloads would immensely help. A nomatch overload for `__iter__(self) -> Any` protocol before old-style protocol would have prevented this. I agree there's no mypy bug here: the typeshed defn is imprecise, and probably can't be corrected within current type system.

6.14.0

Today, we are excited to share the 6.14.0 stable release 🎉

🌟 Star this repo for notifications about new releases, bug fixes & features — or follow us on X!

Highlights

@unique attributes for SQL views (Preview)

Last release, we improved the robustness of SQL views defined in the Prisma schema. Views are virtual tables that don't allows for defining unique constraints, indexes or foreign keys in the underlying database.

However, as an application developer, it can be convenient to also define relationships involving views or paginate them using cursors. We've received this feedback from several people who had been using views in that way with Prisma ORM, so in this release we're re-introducing the @unique attribute for views. This attribute enables:

  • relationships involving views
  • findUnique queries, cursor-based pagination & implicit ordering for views

Here's an example schema using @unique and defining a relationship from a model to a view:

model User {
  id        Int            @id @default(autoincrement())
  email     String         @unique
  posts     Post[]
  stats     UserPostStats? @relation(fields: [email], references: [userEmail])

issue.title: [BUG]
issue.body:
### Oqtane Info

- Version: 6.1.4
- Render Mode: Static
- Interactivity: Server
- Database: SQL Server

### Describe the bug
When attempting to send emails through MailKit in Oqtane, the SMTP connection times out even though:

The mail server (mail186.mailasp.net) works perfectly via command line (OpenSSL/Telnet)

Authentication succeeds in manual tests

The same credentials work outside Oqtane

The timeout occurs specifically during the ConnectAsync or AuthenticateAsync phases when running within Oqtane.

### Expected Behavior
MailKit should successfully connect and authenticate with the SMTP server (port 465) within 30 seconds, just as it does in manual command-line tests.

### Steps To Reproduce
Configure Oqtane SMTP settings with:

Host: mail186.mailasp.net
Port: 465
SSL: True
Authentication: Basic
Valid credentials that work via command line
Trigger any email sending function (e.g. user registration email)

### Observe one of:

30+ second timeout with no response
SocketException/Win32Exception
"The operation has timed out" error

### Anything else?
Workarounds Attempted:
Confirmed server works via OpenSSL/Telnet
Verified credentials are correct
Increased timeout to 60 seconds (no effect)
Tried both ports 465 and 587
Environment Notes:
Occurs on both IIS Express and production IIS
.NET 9 hosting bundle installed
Windows Server 2022 environment
Firewall rules confirmed open for outbound SMTP
Additional Context:
The issue appears specific to Oqtane's DI container or configuration pipeline, as the same MailKit code works in isolation. There may be an interaction between:

- Oqtane's settings provider
- The HttpClientFactory pipeline
- ASP.NET Core's hosting environment

pull_request.title: feat: simplify errors
pull_request.body: ### What I did Simplified error visualisation for non-vyper contracts. Coincidentally addressing this spares us the need to fix error decoding for non Vyper contracts which currently looks like this: Even if I were to fix: 1. the double printing of the trace 2. the error decoding I would end up having a duplicate of what the call tree is already showing. ### How I did it This pull request refactors error handling in the `boa` contracts codebase to introduce a more extensible and contract-specific exception hierarchy. The main change is the creation of a new `BoaError` base exception class, with a specialized `VyperError` subclass for Vyper contracts. This allows for more tailored error messages and stack traces, and enables contract-specific error handling logic. The error handling methods are updated to support this new hierarchy. **Error handling improvements:** * Added a new `BoaError` base exception class in `base_evm_contract.py`, refactored to only display the call trace and not materialize the stack trace unless needed. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-0098dfce477ddba61a9def269ea6cb81a5fd25e60ad3525273a048fbb14c2ebfR17-R32) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-0098dfce477ddba61a9def269ea6cb81a5fd25e60ad3525273a048fbb14c2ebfR1) * Updated the `handle_error` method in `_BaseEVMContract` to accept a customizable `error_type`, enabling contract-specific error handling. **Vyper contract-specific changes:** * Introduced a `VyperError` subclass of `BoaError` in `vyper_contract.py`, restoring the previous stack trace formatting logic for Vyper contracts. * Updated error handling in Vyper contract methods (`_run_init` and `marshal_to_python`) to use `VyperError` for more informative error reporting. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-169defa72cb1b5ca07fb97e039fb200343269e58eb4b344c3a863f63f9e7cd3dL602-R619) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-169defa72cb1b5ca07fb97e039fb200343269e58eb4b344c3a863f63f9e7cd3dL747-R763) **Minor cleanup:** * Removed an unnecessary comment in the `at` method of `VyperContract`. ### How to verify it Compare how errors look like on a VyperContract ```python import boa bar = boa.loads(""" # pragma version 0.4.3 @external def foo(): raise "reason" """) bar.foo() ``` Vs how they look like on an VVMContract (and hence also on ABIContract) ```python import boa bar = boa.loads(""" # pragma version 0.4.2 # 0.4.2 triggers vvm compilation @external def foo(): raise "reason" """) bar.foo() ``` ### Description for the changelog Errors are now easier to read on non-vyper contracts and contain less redundant information.

issue.body:
$2000 USD Bounty here!

If you can find a nice solution to our local dev experience, take home a $2000 USD bounty. We have a very strong feeling the culprit is the App Store. The problem is that refactoring it is a challenge since we have 100+ apps, there are tons of circular dependencies and our `main` branch is constantly merged to, making conflicts hard to work around.

Take these PRs as inspiration to ideally not load the entire App Store upon any given page load in our app. If you debug locally and watch what happens in the `.next/server/chunks` folder, you will see it's compiling a ton of code that's not needed.

These PRs have gotten close but refactoring the test suite to continue passing has been quite a blocker.

https://github.com/calcom/cal.com/pull/22450
https://github.com/calcom/cal.com/pull/19771

Current initial page load times per page even on a beast MacBook Pro can be upwards of 10-12s. **This needs to be cut by at least 80%.**

Now are routers are much more slim (fewer handlers) so pretty sure is that it’s not tRPC directly but instead the dependencies that are loaded as part of tRPC. e.g. if you run “yarn dev” and only load the i18n handler via tRPC, it should be quite fast. 

Have you checked to see which dependencies are loaded as part of the tRPC handler you commented out?

pull_request.title: Fix module loading in logging config
pull_request.body:
## Summary

Fix issue where custom logging configuration with simple module paths (like `log_config.LOGGING_CONFIG`) caused triggerer and scheduler to fail during startup.

## Problem

When users set `logging_config_class = log_config.LOGGING_CONFIG` in their `airflow.cfg`, the `load_logging_config()` function would fail because:

1. `logging_class_path.rsplit(".", 1)[0]` produces `"log_config"`
2. `import_string("log_config")` fails because it expects a dot-separated path like `"module.submodule.attribute"`
3. This caused `ImportError` and prevented `REMOTE_TASK_LOG` and `DEFAULT_REMOTE_CONN_ID` from being loaded
4. In some environments, this prevented triggerer and scheduler from starting

## Solution

Replace `import_string()` with `importlib.import_module()` in `load_logging_config()`

## Changes

### Code
- in`airflow-core/src/airflow/logging_config.py`, with`load_logging_config()`

### Test
- in `airflow-core/tests/unit/core/test_logging_config.py`
- **Added**: Parametrized test for different module path structures
- **Added**: Test for graceful fallback when remote logging vars are missing
- **Added**: Helper method to reduce test code duplication

## Related Issues

resolves #54414
